findings.recommendation:
On ON_PAUSE, stop the AudioRecord synchronously BEFORE the animation, so the hardware is silenced immediately while the UI slide-down continues for visual polish. Minimal change:
```kotlin
LifecycleEventEffect(Lifecycle.Event.ON_PAUSE) {
    // Silence the mic synchronously on background/call/lock — the sheet's
    // slide-down animation can continue without the hardware open (AC-19).
    runCatching {
        recorderRef.recorder?.let { r ->
            if (r.recordingState == AudioRecord.RECORDSTATE_RECORDING) r.stop()
        }
    }
    recorderRef.job?.cancel()
    onPauseDismiss()
}
```
The DisposableEffect still runs `release()` on actual teardown — this just narrows the capture window to "until ON_PAUSE fires" instead of "until the animation completes".

Acceptable as implemented under D27 (mirrors the precedent decision for "camera" in Task 8). If the 200-char cap ever needs to shrink further for audio specifically, sanitize at the VM layer before calling `errorLog.e`:
```kotlin
fun reportAudioError(description: String, cause: Throwable?) {
    val safeCause = cause?.let { RuntimeException(it::class.simpleName) }
    viewModelScope.launch { errorLog.e("audio", description, safeCause) }
    _snackbar.tryEmit(R.string.audio_record_init_failed)
}
```
No change required now — documenting the decision trail.

Optional: also gate the error catch on `completed` for stricter exactly-once delivery:
```kotlin
} catch (t: Throwable) {
    if (completed.compareAndSet(false, true)) {
        onError("audio record read failed", t)
    }
}
```
Not blocking — the VM-layer guards (`addAudio` idempotency, snackbar dedup via MutableSharedFlow) already absorb the race. Flagging for consistency with the `finish` path.
